'''Hogging''' or '''sweat hogging''' refers to the practice of groups of men who target [[overweight]] or [[obese]] women, typically for sexual encounters. Unlike [[fat fetishism|fat fetishists]], men who participate in hogging are not necessarily sexually attracted to obese women's bodies; they aim to take advantage of a female's [[stereotype|stereotypical]] low [[self-esteem]] or to derive amusement for themselves and their friends by engaging in sexual activities with women who are overweight.
== Practice == The social practice can be undertaken as an individual or group activity, and often includes excessive [[Alcohol intoxication|alcohol consumption]], [[emotional detachment]], and degradation of the woman. Hogging does not always include [[sexual intercourse]], and often other sexual activities are the end goal. Participation sometimes includes making bets among male peers, as well as humiliating the woman involved.<ref name=":0">{{cite web | last =Fenske | first =Sarah | title =Big Game Hunters | publisher =Village Voice Media | date = 2003-10-01 | work = [[Cleveland Scene]] | url =http://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/big-game-hunters/Content?oid=1484039 | accessdate =2007-09-23 }}</ref>
== Criticism == Hogging has been described as a form of [[misogyny]], and as part of culturally-sanctioned abuse of women in the [[United States]],<ref name=":1">{{Citation|title="Knocking off a Fat Girl:" An Exploration of Hogging, Male Sexuality, and Neutralizations|date=|url=|year=2006|last1=Gailey|last2=Prohaska|first1=Jeannine|first2=Ariane|authorlink1=|authorlink2=|journal=[[Deviant Behavior (journal)|Deviant Behavior]]|volume=27|issue=1|pages=31–49|doi=|id=}}</ref> although the activity has also been observed in Australia.<ref name="McShaneWilliams2007">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DWas8uhuEZIC&pg=PA90|title=Youth Violence and Delinquency &#91;Three Volumes&#93;|author1=Marilyn D. McShane|author2=Franklin P. Williams|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-08204-7|pages=}}</ref> Donna Jarrell, lecturer at [[Ohio State University]] and author of ''What Are You Looking At?: the First Fat Fiction Anthology,'' described hogging as a "sad" practice, saying that it reveals how "our attraction or our revulsion to fat has a lot to do with our culture". She commented that the fat [[Social stigma|stigma]] is so extreme that even men who are genuinely attracted to overweight women cannot admit or discuss their feelings.<ref name=":0" />
The practice has also been suggested as a manifestation of [[hypermasculinity]], in which men who do not fit into normative expectations of manhood exhibit insecurity, defensiveness, and sexual aggression to make up for their incapacity to meet masculine standards. In this manner, hogging is described as a form of [[sexual predation]] in which sex is an act of conquest, not intimacy.<ref name="McShaneWilliams2007" />
