{{New Testament manuscript infobox | form = Papyrus | number= {{Papyrus|2}} | image= Papyrus 2 - Egyptian Museum, Florence, inv. nr. 7134 - John 12,12-15 Luke 7,22-26.50.jpg | caption= no image available | name = | text = [[Gospel of John|John]] 12:12-15; [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] 7:22-26.50 | date = c. 550 | found= [[Egypt]] | now at= [[National Archaeological Museum (Florence)|Museo Archeologico]], [[Florence]], Inv. Nr. 7134 | cite = [[:it:Ermenegildo Pistelli|E. Pistelli]], 'Papiri evangelici', ''Rivista di Studi Religiosi'' '''6''' (1902): 69-70. | size = fragment | type = mixed | cat = III | hand = | note = }} '''Papyrus 2''' ({{Papyrus|2}}) is an early copy of the New Testament in Greek and Coptic. It is a [[papyrus]] fragment of a copy of the [[Gospel of John]] dating to the sixth century. It is currently housed at the [[Egyptian Museum, Florence]] (Inv. no. 7134).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://intf.uni-muenster.de/vmr/NTVMR/ListeHandschriften.php?ObjID=10002|title=Online copy of the MS|publisher=Institute for New Testament Textual Research|accessdate=13 August 2011|location=Münster}}</ref> There is a portion of [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] 7:22-26.50 in [[Coptic language|Coptic]] on the reverse of the fragment.
The fragment appears to be from a [[lectionary]].<ref>Maldfeld, Georg and [[Bruce Metzger|Metzger, Bruce M.]] "Detailed List of the Greek Papyri of the New Testament," ''Journal of Biblical Literature'' Vol. 68, No. 4. (Dec., 1949), p. 361</ref> The text type is a mixed.<ref>Maldfeld (1949), p. 364</ref> [[Kurt Aland|Aland]] placed it in [[Categories of New Testament manuscripts#Category III|Category III]].<ref name = Aland>{{Cite book |last=Aland |first=Kurt |authorlink=Kurt Aland | last2 = Aland | first2 = Barbara | authorlink2 = Barbara Aland | others = Erroll F. Rhodes (trans.) |title=The Text of the New Testament: An Introduction to the Critical Editions and to the Theory and Practice of Modern Textual Criticism |publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]] |year=1995 |location=Grand Rapids |page=96 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pYDsAhUOxAC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=falsee |isbn=978-0-8028-4098-1}}</ref>
Name of city ιεροσολυμα (Jerusalem) is given in variation ιερου[σο]λ̣υ̣[μα].
[[Ermenegildo Pistelli]] dated the manuscript to the 5th or 6th century; [[Ernst von Dobschütz]] to the 6th or 7th century.<ref>[http://nttranscripts.uni-muenster.de/AnaServer?NTtranscripts+0+start.anv New Testament Transcripts]</ref>
